05:13.312 --> 05:14.561
Hang in there.

05:16.167 --> 05:17.598
Trauma Bay 10.

05:17.600 --> 05:19.314
When the paramedics called this in,

05:19.316 --> 05:20.625
I wouldn't have guessed
you were with them.

05:20.627 --> 05:22.177
Yeah, trust me, I didn't
expect to be here either.

05:22.179 --> 05:23.821
- Who's the trauma surgeon on today?
- Bell.

05:23.823 --> 05:26.413
- He's already on his way.
- Correction. He's already here.

05:26.415 --> 05:28.475
Hawkins, you care to explain
how you ended up here,

05:28.477 --> 05:29.851
yet again, with a patient?

05:29.853 --> 05:31.995
I was at the practice
center when Dax got injured.

05:31.997 --> 05:33.795
- All right, what do we have?
- 19-year-old male,

05:33.797 --> 05:35.431
blunt trauma to the chest and abdomen.

05:35.433 --> 05:38.001
Hypotensive and tachycardic en route.

05:38.003 --> 05:39.319
(DAX GROANS)

05:39.321 --> 05:41.184
I'm Dr. Feldman, this is Dr. Bell.

05:41.186 --> 05:42.247
Do you have any allergies

05:42.249 --> 05:43.490
to any medications we should know about?

05:43.492 --> 05:44.508
Not that I know of.

05:44.510 --> 05:46.376
Nice as it is to see you, Conrad,

05:46.378 --> 05:48.661
- Logan Kim isn't going to like that you're here.
- I know.

05:48.663 --> 05:50.879
I can't just leave him
while he's still in pain.

05:50.881 --> 05:51.988
Hey, Conrad?

05:51.990 --> 05:54.478
Yeah, I'm here. We're
gonna take care of you.

05:54.480 --> 05:55.985
I'm a friend of the patient,

05:55.987 --> 05:58.004
that's not against hospital policy.

05:58.006 --> 06:00.858
- (GROANS)
- (ALARM BEEPING)

06:00.860 --> 06:03.702
Okay, his O2 stats are dropping.
We need to intubate him.

06:05.308 --> 06:08.167
- Chest cavity is full of blood.
- Get me a chest tube kit.

06:08.868 --> 06:10.425
Now, as the friend of the patient,

06:10.427 --> 06:12.550
I'm gonna have to ask you to
step outside the trauma bay.

06:12.552 --> 06:14.279
- That is hospital policy.
- I understand.

06:14.281 --> 06:16.457
I'm playing by the rules on this one.

06:24.407 --> 06:27.367
<i>MAN (OVER P.A.): Dr. Lee
to Infectious Disease.</i>

06:27.369 --> 06:29.303
(PHONE RINGING)

06:30.829 --> 06:32.427
Hey, Dad. I was just on my way out.

06:32.429 --> 06:33.913
Where are you? I'll pick you up.

06:35.877 --> 06:37.511
You're where?

06:37.513 --> 06:39.480
- (SIREN WAILING)
- (INDISTINCT RADIO CHATTER)

06:42.976 --> 06:44.643
It's fine. I'm fine.

06:44.645 --> 06:46.478
You're not fine. You got arrested.

06:46.480 --> 06:48.238
You see any handcuffs? I'm okay.

06:48.240 --> 06:51.057
Can we just please go?

06:51.059 --> 06:53.577
What the hell happened?
You got into a fight?

06:53.579 --> 06:56.464
- It was schoolyard stuff.
- Between two grown men?

06:56.466 --> 06:57.788
Well, he threw the first punch.

06:57.790 --> 06:59.941
The police agree that I'm
innocent, so they released me.

06:59.943 --> 07:02.828
- Who were you fighting?
- This guy, he bought my car.

07:02.830 --> 07:05.295
He had buyer's remorse, he
thought I'd take it back.

07:05.297 --> 07:08.241
- And then he made fun of my hat.
- Wait, you-you sold your car?

07:08.243 --> 07:10.618
You've had that car for 20 years.

07:10.620 --> 07:12.245
Nic, nothing lasts forever.

07:12.247 --> 07:13.631
Dad.

07:13.633 --> 07:17.008
- I'm worried about you.
- (PANTING)

07:17.010 --> 07:20.643
Yes, look... Okay, I've
been a-a little down lately.

07:20.645 --> 07:23.102
But who doesn't hit a rough
patch every now and then?

07:23.104 --> 07:25.438
I'm fine.

07:26.094 --> 07:27.820
I promise.

07:33.506 --> 07:36.029
AUSTIN: Well, the repeat
cultures are negative.

07:36.031 --> 07:37.955
Plus no fever in two days.

07:37.957 --> 07:40.815
Which means your infection is clearing.

07:40.817 --> 07:43.484
So I finally get to hold my baby?

07:43.486 --> 07:44.853
Yes, indeed.

07:44.855 --> 07:48.789
However, the results
happen to be so good that...

07:48.791 --> 07:52.377
We can discharge you and send
you home with oral antibiotics.

07:52.379 --> 07:54.287
Yes! Ah...

07:54.289 --> 07:57.832
Thank you both so much for everything.

07:57.834 --> 08:00.491
- You got it.
- I can't wait to have Michelle in my arms

08:00.493 --> 08:02.554
- and finally to be able to get out of here.
- Mm-hmm.

08:02.556 --> 08:04.723
(SIGHS)

08:04.725 --> 08:07.223
Do you think she'll know who I am?

08:07.225 --> 08:09.715
I'm sure she'll know

08:09.717 --> 08:12.155
by the love you give her.

08:12.157 --> 08:13.699
(CHUCKLES)

08:14.976 --> 08:17.327
- ADAKU: Look at how cute she is.
- MINA: Yeah.

08:17.329 --> 08:19.854
(EXHALES)

08:19.856 --> 08:21.147
As my admitting resident,

08:21.149 --> 08:23.333
you are gatekeeper
to the medicine floor.

08:23.335 --> 08:24.576
And when I say "gatekeeper",

08:24.578 --> 08:27.057
I mean you are to be a blocking machine.

08:27.059 --> 08:30.663
Mrs. Allen, 68-year-old female
with alcoholic pancreatitis.

08:30.665 --> 08:32.006
Know what went wrong here?

08:32.008 --> 08:34.482
She binged on alcohol and
gave herself pancreatitis?

08:34.485 --> 08:36.884
Wrong. The ER were too
slow giving her a benzo,

08:36.885 --> 08:38.664
so now we're stuck chasing
her withdrawal symptoms.

08:38.667 --> 08:40.556
That's not entirely
fair. The ER is always...

08:40.558 --> 08:42.876
Mr. Hopper, 80-year-old man.

08:42.879 --> 08:44.879
Fell in his home, sprained his hip.

08:44.881 --> 08:45.914
Care to guess the mistake?

08:45.916 --> 08:48.600
He's an elderly man who lives alone

08:48.602 --> 08:51.353
- and he needs discharge planning.
- Which could have been done

08:51.355 --> 08:53.605
while he was waiting in the
ER. Instead, he's taking up

08:53.607 --> 08:55.181
one of our beds,
waiting for a placement.

08:55.183 --> 08:57.200
I could go on, but the trend is clear.

08:57.202 --> 09:00.704
We're accepting patients from
the ER that don't belong here.

09:00.706 --> 09:03.231
Look, I agree that these patients

09:03.233 --> 09:05.191
in particular could
have been managed better,

09:05.193 --> 09:08.003
but most of the patients on
this floor do need to be here.

09:11.625 --> 09:15.218
I know you're not a
pure medicine resident,

09:15.220 --> 09:18.388
that you've been tainted by
habits you learned in the ER.

09:18.390 --> 09:22.559
- I wouldn't say that...
- But you're on this team now.

09:22.561 --> 09:24.353
So, what are you going to be?

09:26.256 --> 09:27.880
A blocking machine.

09:27.882 --> 09:31.318
A blocking... machine.

09:33.263 --> 09:36.198
(BUSY CHATTER)

09:37.892 --> 09:39.576
Dr. Hawkins...

09:39.578 --> 09:43.396
this is Bill Landry,
owner of Georgia FC.

09:43.398 --> 09:45.924
Son, I have a team of top
doctors from St. John's

09:45.926 --> 09:47.123
who take care of my players.

09:47.125 --> 09:49.610
I don't know who you are
or why you were on my field.

09:49.612 --> 09:52.255
Why exactly did you poach
a patient from St. John's

09:52.257 --> 09:53.749
- and bring him here?
- That's not what happened.

09:53.751 --> 09:54.758
I don't care.

09:54.760 --> 09:57.061
I want Dax transferred to
St. John's immediately.

09:57.063 --> 09:58.929
Well, that would be a bad idea.

09:58.931 --> 10:02.415
Dax has sustained significant
injuries to his chest

10:02.417 --> 10:04.843
and his abdomen, leading
to multiple broken ribs,

10:04.845 --> 10:07.295
lung contusions,
lacerations to his spleen.

10:07.297 --> 10:09.255
I trust that, when he stabilizes,

10:09.257 --> 10:11.399
you'll make that transfer
happen as soon as possible.

10:11.401 --> 10:12.592
Y-You have my word.

10:12.594 --> 10:16.245
And I apologize for the
inconvenience. I-I hope...

10:20.119 --> 10:22.894
Bill Landry is the
richest man in Georgia,

10:22.896 --> 10:25.646
and in one morning you have
him pissed off at Chastain.

10:25.648 --> 10:28.649
You shouldn't have been anywhere
near Dax Ramsey to begin with.

10:28.651 --> 10:30.683
He asked for a second
opinion, so I helped.

10:30.685 --> 10:34.781
He's at Chastain now, so your
services are no longer required.

10:34.783 --> 10:35.929
Treating a patient

10:35.931 --> 10:38.213
without hospital privileges
is against the law.

10:38.215 --> 10:40.161
I'm not treating him.

10:40.163 --> 10:41.363
I'm here as a friend.

10:41.365 --> 10:44.883
Which gives Dr. Hawkins
every right to stay.

10:44.885 --> 10:47.643
If you so much as lay
a finger on Dax Ramsey,

10:47.645 --> 10:49.813
I'll have you thrown out and sued.

11:05.539 --> 11:07.779
Wow. You guys already boarding
patients in the hallway?

11:07.781 --> 11:09.315
One of those days.

11:09.317 --> 11:11.859
- You here for my admit?
- First one of the day.

11:11.861 --> 11:15.203
Riley, this is Dr. Pravesh.
He's gonna do an assessment.

11:15.205 --> 11:17.248
Okay. (CLEARS THROAT)
Hey, can I do the thing?

11:17.250 --> 11:18.953
The floor is yours.

11:18.955 --> 11:21.419
Riley Jackson, 28-year-old female.

11:21.421 --> 11:24.992
Five hours of sudden
onset nausea and vomiting.

11:24.994 --> 11:27.258
- Did I get it right?
- Nailed it.

11:27.260 --> 11:29.335
And that's vomiting with a capital "V".

11:29.337 --> 11:31.429
I can't even keep crackers down.

11:31.431 --> 11:33.356
It's good to meet you, Riley.

11:33.358 --> 11:35.175
Uh, can you tell me
when all this started?

11:35.177 --> 11:36.434
Uh, this morning.

11:36.436 --> 11:39.178
I woke up fine, dropped
my daughter off at school.

11:39.180 --> 11:40.555
And then on the drive back home...

11:40.557 --> 11:41.889
- Capital "V"?
- Yeah.

11:41.891 --> 11:43.652
- Hmm.
- All over my steering wheel.

11:43.654 --> 11:44.890
It was not pretty.

11:44.892 --> 11:46.584
Okay. I'm gonna talk to
Dr. Feldman and figure out

11:46.586 --> 11:48.836
- the best way to take care of you, okay?
- Thank you so much.

11:48.838 --> 11:51.950
- All right. We'll be right back.
- Thanks.

11:51.952 --> 11:53.860
Hey, this looks like gastroenteritis.

11:53.862 --> 11:55.194
- This is a soft admit.
- Yeah...

11:55.196 --> 11:56.863
Got you there, Feldman.

11:56.865 --> 11:59.290
Give it a few more hours of
continuous fluids and meds.

11:59.292 --> 12:02.869
Are you seriously
blocking this admission?

12:02.871 --> 12:07.019
Wow, you've, uh, already
become one of them.

12:07.021 --> 12:09.717
(CHUCKLES) Stashing a patient
in the ER for a couple hours,

12:09.719 --> 12:11.136
hoping they somehow cure themselves?

12:11.138 --> 12:13.063
- Internal medicine's signature move.
- DEVON: Look,

12:13.065 --> 12:15.306
I can't give Riley a
bed that doesn't exist.

12:15.308 --> 12:17.298
Between surgical patients
and medical patients,

12:17.300 --> 12:18.891
- a bed isn't available.
- That's true.

12:18.893 --> 12:20.553
They got a lot of
surgical patients today.

12:20.555 --> 12:22.269
- You know, how about you just pick a side, man?
- Pick a side.

12:22.271 --> 12:24.891
Sorry. I like watching you two argue.

12:24.893 --> 12:28.728
My therapist says it's because
I envy your guys' relationship.

12:28.730 --> 12:29.871
Which I do not.

12:33.197 --> 12:35.135
Just because you're busy
upstairs doesn't mean

12:35.137 --> 12:36.661
you get to saddle us with your work.

12:36.663 --> 12:40.331
We don't exactly, uh, have
spare time down here either.

12:40.333 --> 12:43.743
Fine. I'll put in holding orders.

12:43.745 --> 12:46.189
But she will have to board in the ER

12:46.191 --> 12:47.672
until a bed is available.

12:47.674 --> 12:50.350
As long as she's not on my list,
you can do whatever you want.

12:54.130 --> 12:56.014
Look who's here.

12:56.016 --> 12:57.983
(CRYING): Hi.

13:00.428 --> 13:01.969
(LAUGHS): Hi.

13:01.971 --> 13:04.856
(SNIFFLES) I'm your mom.

13:04.858 --> 13:08.026
And you're the most beautiful
thing in the whole world.

13:08.028 --> 13:11.454
<i>♪ I had a dream ♪</i>

13:11.456 --> 13:12.697
<i>♪ I got everything I wanted... ♪</i>

13:12.699 --> 13:14.791
Put your finger in her palm.

13:14.793 --> 13:17.944
Can you grab this? Grab this.

13:17.946 --> 13:21.489
Here. (LAUGHS)

13:21.491 --> 13:23.633
Thank you, Mina.

13:23.635 --> 13:25.635
For everything.

13:25.637 --> 13:27.712
<i>♪ To anyone who might care... ♪</i>

13:27.714 --> 13:30.807
Hi. Hi.

13:30.809 --> 13:33.885
You like my finger? (LAUGHS)

13:33.887 --> 13:35.312
Here.

13:35.314 --> 13:36.337
<i>♪ I got everything I wanted ♪</i>

13:36.339 --> 13:38.464
Hi.

13:38.466 --> 13:39.724
<i>♪ But when I wake... ♪</i>

13:39.726 --> 13:41.693
Hi.

13:53.999 --> 13:56.190
Oh. Hey, hey.

13:56.192 --> 13:58.760
Hey, hey. You don't got to walk me in.

13:58.762 --> 14:00.760
Oh, well, I want to
take a look at that cut.

14:00.762 --> 14:02.986
- It could get infected.
- I-I got bandages

14:02.988 --> 14:05.355
and all sorts of antiseptic stuff.

14:05.357 --> 14:06.993
I'll be fine.

14:06.995 --> 14:09.186
Okay, well, I thought we were
gonna spend the day together.

14:09.188 --> 14:10.922
You... still want to do that, or... ?

14:10.924 --> 14:12.757
Well, yeah. Sure, sure. Yeah, of course.

14:12.759 --> 14:15.260
I just, I'd like to clean up and...

14:15.262 --> 14:17.095
My place is a mess and, uh...

14:17.097 --> 14:20.598
Tell you what, why don't we
grab lunch a little later?

14:20.600 --> 14:22.776
Sure, yeah. I'll call you in a bit.

14:48.962 --> 14:50.929
(KNOCKING ON DOOR)

14:56.061 --> 14:57.560
(KYLE COUGHS)

14:57.562 --> 14:59.312
(SIGHS)

15:02.545 --> 15:05.980
Were you at least gonna tell
me that you were leaving again?

15:08.765 --> 15:10.073
No.

15:12.935 --> 15:14.652
I thought you were in trouble.

15:14.654 --> 15:17.655
I told you I was fine.

15:17.657 --> 15:19.607
Things have been so good between us,

15:19.609 --> 15:22.234
and you want to throw it all away? Why?

15:22.236 --> 15:25.893
S-Settling down, volunteering
at Chastain, being an angel,

15:25.895 --> 15:29.000
trying to be a good dad
to you, it's exhausting.

15:29.002 --> 15:31.970
- I can't do it anymore.
- So you're just gonna take off again?

15:33.673 --> 15:38.009
Nicky, I burn down every good thing

15:38.011 --> 15:40.270
that's ever happened to me.

15:42.423 --> 15:44.065
That's who I am.

15:47.428 --> 15:51.138
I'm sorry I led you to believe
that, even for a second,

15:51.140 --> 15:52.932
that I had changed.

15:52.934 --> 15:55.360
I... Here.

15:55.362 --> 15:57.912
Here, I want you to have this.

15:58.981 --> 16:02.400
It's money from the car.

16:02.402 --> 16:04.819
I wanted to leave you
something f-for the... sh...

16:04.821 --> 16:08.373
I-I don't know, for all
the, for all the time

16:08.375 --> 16:11.301
that you-you wasted on me.

16:11.303 --> 16:14.220
Come on, please. Here.

16:17.550 --> 16:19.934
(DOOR OPENS, CLOSES)

16:29.488 --> 16:31.620
But his history is unremarkable.

16:31.622 --> 16:32.903
Nothing is jumping out at me.

16:32.905 --> 16:35.683
Whoa. If I knew it was you

16:35.685 --> 16:38.008
on the other end of the page,
I would've rallied the troops,

16:38.010 --> 16:39.741
signaled the alarm, called the band...

16:39.743 --> 16:42.133
Can you just say it's good to
see him and be done with it?

16:42.135 --> 16:44.575
- Thanks for coming down, Austin.
- No problem.

16:44.577 --> 16:47.361
I see we're hiding out
in the conference room.

16:47.363 --> 16:48.897
Avoiding Logan Kim, I take it?

16:48.899 --> 16:51.416
And the appearance that I'm
treating a patient in Chastain.

16:51.418 --> 16:53.048
A loophole. I dig it. What's up?

16:53.050 --> 16:55.661
Dax Ramsey. He has a chest
tube, a lacerated spleen,

16:55.663 --> 16:57.371
and multiple pulmonary
contusions with hemorrhage.

16:57.373 --> 16:59.028
Do you think he'll need surgery?

16:59.030 --> 17:02.543
His chest tube is only draining
a hundred mils per hour.

17:02.545 --> 17:04.429
So we have to wait and watch and hope

17:04.431 --> 17:06.276
that his lungs heal itself.

17:06.278 --> 17:08.766
If not, I will come in
and save the day, but...

17:08.768 --> 17:12.436
Taking off my thoracic hat and
putting on my trauma fedora...

17:12.439 --> 17:14.186
- Bell, are you seeing what I'm seeing?
- BELL: Yeah.

17:14.189 --> 17:16.140
The injuries are severe
for the trauma he took.

17:16.142 --> 17:17.678
Uh, we were just getting to that.

17:17.680 --> 17:19.700
Is... Any idea why he
wanted a second opinion?

17:19.702 --> 17:21.125
Yeah, over the years, Dax has suffered

17:21.127 --> 17:22.204
more injuries than normal.

17:22.207 --> 17:24.898
He thought maybe his team
doctor missed something.

17:24.901 --> 17:26.890
Yeah, well, I think
Dax was onto something.

17:26.892 --> 17:29.249
- Mm-hmm.
- (PAGER BEEPING)

17:29.251 --> 17:31.018
Dax is crashing.

17:32.575 --> 17:34.200
You might want to hang back, bro.

17:34.202 --> 17:37.554
Our patient is critical. I
can't worry about the rules.

17:37.556 --> 17:38.638
(RAPID BEEPING)

17:40.793 --> 17:42.867
Get a crash cart. He's in V fib.

17:42.869 --> 17:44.268
His sats are down to the 80s.

17:44.270 --> 17:46.771
Hawkins, I need you to do compressions.

17:47.807 --> 17:50.641
Do it. Abdomen's soft.

17:50.643 --> 17:52.902
There's no blood in his
drainage system either.

17:55.148 --> 17:57.890
(CONRAD GRUNTING)

17:57.892 --> 17:59.942
We need to decompress his chest.

18:15.576 --> 18:19.554
He's back in sinus tach,
but he's still hypotensive.

18:20.840 --> 18:22.515
You ready? Get it.

18:28.607 --> 18:30.297
Massive hemothorax.

18:30.299 --> 18:32.660
We need to get Dax to surgery now.

18:32.662 --> 18:33.662
BELL: Give me the bag.

18:35.661 --> 18:37.470
CONRAD: Let's go.

18:39.976 --> 18:43.328
I told you what would happen if
I caught you treating a patient.

18:45.182 --> 18:46.922
It was compressions.

18:46.924 --> 18:49.167
For a patient who would
have died otherwise.

18:49.169 --> 18:51.136
It's okay.

18:54.541 --> 18:56.925
- Take care of Dax.
- Yeah.

19:13.726 --> 19:16.727
Well, the lobectomy should keep
Dax's bleeding under control.

19:16.729 --> 19:19.346
We solved one issue, and
another keeps sprouting up.

19:19.348 --> 19:21.157
- You notice his legs were swollen?
- Yeah.

19:21.159 --> 19:24.643
I also saw what looked
like blood in his urine bag.

19:24.645 --> 19:26.996
- He's in rhabdo.
- But why exactly

19:26.998 --> 19:29.023
is his muscle tissue breaking down?

19:29.025 --> 19:31.668
His pH is normal. At
least he's not acidotic.

19:31.670 --> 19:33.670
You know, maybe it's a mixed picture.

19:33.672 --> 19:36.322
Metabolic acidosis plus
respiratory alkalosis.

19:36.324 --> 19:39.008
What is going on with this kid?

19:39.010 --> 19:40.898
You know, the only
thing I know for certain

19:40.900 --> 19:42.253
is we'll figure it out.

19:42.255 --> 19:45.756
No doubt. No, a theory
will come to us in a minute.

19:45.758 --> 19:47.141
We got this.

19:52.006 --> 19:54.340
So it's not coming to
us at-at this m-moment.

19:54.342 --> 19:56.675
Well, w-we... you know, Bell,
we have nothing to prove.

19:56.677 --> 19:58.769
You know, you have a
bomb-ass supplement line

19:58.771 --> 20:00.558
- taking off right now.
- You're a triple-board-certified surgeon.

20:00.560 --> 20:02.550
- Right?
- The reality is, we are out of our wheelhouse.

20:02.552 --> 20:05.392
- Well, that's fair.
- This is much less of a surgical case

20:05.394 --> 20:07.036
- and more of a medical...
- It, uh, is a mystery.

20:07.038 --> 20:08.871
There you go.

20:13.620 --> 20:15.235
I never thought I'd say these words.

20:15.237 --> 20:17.696
Oh, go ahead, say it.

20:17.698 --> 20:19.698
One of us has to, Bell.

20:19.700 --> 20:22.918
- We might need Conrad Hawkins.
- Now, did that hurt much?

20:22.920 --> 20:25.037
- Yeah, a little.
- Okay.

20:25.039 --> 20:30.226
Look, he can't come here, so
we got to make a house call.

20:30.228 --> 20:33.471
So far, we've only been treating
the trauma-related injuries.

20:33.473 --> 20:35.565
Injuries exacerbated by an underlying,

20:35.567 --> 20:37.642
- undiagnosed condition.
- Right.

20:37.644 --> 20:39.551
CONRAD: We've seen his
records. What do we know?

20:39.553 --> 20:40.970
BELL: He typically experiences vomiting

20:40.972 --> 20:42.238
after strenuous workouts.

20:42.240 --> 20:44.649
And most recently, he's
been suffering a string

20:44.651 --> 20:47.827
of musculoskeletal
injuries and now has rhabdo.

20:51.157 --> 20:53.774
I know that look.

20:53.776 --> 20:55.567
You know, I dig that look.

20:55.569 --> 20:58.112
It's been an acquired taste for me.

20:58.114 --> 21:00.423
(EXHALES)

21:00.425 --> 21:03.409
He's not septic. And
while the rhabdo alone

21:03.411 --> 21:05.002
can cause some elevation in the lactate,

21:05.004 --> 21:06.304
it's more than I'd expect.

21:08.007 --> 21:11.017
I think we're seeing...

21:12.753 --> 21:15.421
Type B lactic acidosis.

21:15.423 --> 21:18.866
In plain English, there's
something that's preventing Dax

21:18.868 --> 21:21.278
from breaking down
glucose in the normal way.

21:21.280 --> 21:22.594
How do you treat that?

21:22.596 --> 21:25.712
Type B lactic acidosis is
a symptom of something else.

21:25.714 --> 21:27.536
And it's that something

21:27.538 --> 21:29.394
that might explain what's been causing

21:29.396 --> 21:31.362
all of Dax's injuries
in the first place.

21:31.364 --> 21:34.123
Well, you guys seem to
know what you're doing.

21:34.125 --> 21:36.276
Guess it's good that Dax landed here.

21:36.278 --> 21:38.736
We only employ the best at Chastain.

21:39.514 --> 21:40.661
Thank you.

21:40.663 --> 21:43.098
Mm-hmm. You bet.

21:45.453 --> 21:48.454
Surgeons usually don't possess
such an in-depth knowledge

21:48.456 --> 21:49.722
of medical management.

21:52.334 --> 21:54.835
Um, well, I'm sorry,

21:54.837 --> 21:58.105
last time I checked,
you weren't a doctor.

21:58.107 --> 22:00.674
AUSTIN: Yeah, so why don't you run along

22:00.676 --> 22:03.561
and worry about whatever
it is you worry about?

22:03.563 --> 22:05.655
And you let us focus
on saving our patient.

22:09.879 --> 22:12.102
Nurse Ingrid, have you
checked on Riley Jackson?

22:12.104 --> 22:13.152
I don't see her on the floor.

22:13.154 --> 22:14.870
I don't know who that is.
Is she a medicine patient?

22:14.872 --> 22:17.342
I admitted her two hours ago,
and we have open beds now.

22:17.344 --> 22:19.242
Do you know why she
hasn't been brought up?

22:19.244 --> 22:21.838
I can tell you, Pravesh.
Canceled her admission.

22:21.840 --> 22:24.700
I told you to be a blocking machine,

22:24.702 --> 22:27.367
but instead you let your
friend from ER run over you.

22:27.369 --> 22:30.018
No, that's not what happened.
I made a compromise

22:30.020 --> 22:32.256
to ease the tension
between our departments.

22:32.258 --> 22:34.581
Who are you, Oprah?

22:34.583 --> 22:37.603
Since we haven't checked on
her, hopefully the ER has.

22:42.825 --> 22:43.958
Riley?

22:44.845 --> 22:46.011
Riley?

22:46.013 --> 22:47.179
(GROANING SOFTLY)

22:47.181 --> 22:49.031
Open your eyes.

22:49.033 --> 22:52.410
Pupils dilated, minimally reactive.

22:55.387 --> 22:57.410
She's having a stroke.

22:57.412 --> 22:58.908
Let's go.

22:58.910 --> 23:01.571
- Hey, I have a code stroke here.
- Three.

23:01.573 --> 23:04.881
Code stroke, ER Bay Three.

23:04.883 --> 23:07.249
Code stroke, ER Bay Three.

23:07.251 --> 23:08.626
I need an intubation kit.

23:08.628 --> 23:10.519
Draw up 20 of etomidate and 70 of roc.

23:10.521 --> 23:13.080
Okay, once we get better access,
let's get the portable monitor

23:13.082 --> 23:16.542
and get her to CT. She came
in with nausea and vomiting.

23:16.544 --> 23:19.228
How did this happen?

23:22.308 --> 23:24.233
(PHONE RINGING)

23:27.313 --> 23:29.814
(SIGHS)

23:29.816 --> 23:32.149
Hey, how is it going with Kyle?

23:32.151 --> 23:34.151
<i>NIC: Not good.</i>

23:34.153 --> 23:36.162
He's leaving Atlanta.

23:37.565 --> 23:39.490
Wasn't even gonna tell me.

23:39.492 --> 23:41.275
<i>Nic, I'm so sorry.</i>

23:41.277 --> 23:44.587
I let my guard down.

23:44.589 --> 23:47.573
- I let him back into my life. <i>
- Well...</i>

23:47.575 --> 23:50.409
you thought he changed, so did I.

23:50.411 --> 23:52.094
<i>I should have known better.</i>

23:52.096 --> 23:54.913
I mean, he always bails.

23:54.915 --> 23:57.967
He usually tells me some
lie as to why it's best.

23:57.969 --> 24:01.795
This time, he didn't even
bother to lie. He's just...

24:01.797 --> 24:03.180
he's just leaving.

24:03.182 --> 24:04.756
<i>Bell and Austin know how to reach me.</i>

24:04.758 --> 24:05.917
<i>Why don't I pack up,</i>

24:05.919 --> 24:08.923
come home, and we turn this horrible day

24:08.925 --> 24:10.304
into something else?

24:10.306 --> 24:12.782
It's okay.

24:12.784 --> 24:14.617
I think I just need some time.

24:14.619 --> 24:18.696
Okay.

24:18.698 --> 24:21.773
But you call me the
second you need anything.

24:21.775 --> 24:26.170
<i>- I love you.</i>
- I love you, too.

24:30.159 --> 24:32.051
(SNIFFLES)

24:33.454 --> 24:35.263
(SIGHS)

24:37.809 --> 24:38.933
I can't do it anymore.

24:41.387 --> 24:43.629
<i>I'm sorry that I led you to believe</i>

24:43.631 --> 24:45.631
<i>that-that-that it was
different, even for a second.</i>

24:45.633 --> 24:48.008
<i>(NIC LAUGHING)</i>

24:48.010 --> 24:50.778
<i>(INDISTINCT, OVERLAPPING CHATTER)</i>

24:52.973 --> 24:54.490
<i>(LAUGHTER)</i>

24:56.160 --> 24:57.800
<i>KYLE: First day on the
job as a volunteer.</i>

25:05.027 --> 25:07.920
You're all I got, kid.

25:10.032 --> 25:12.425
He did lie.

25:19.041 --> 25:20.641
(LINE RINGING)

25:22.929 --> 25:24.896
(PHONE BUZZING)

25:44.116 --> 25:46.083
♪♪

25:57.538 --> 25:59.263
(MICHELLE CRYING)

26:02.227 --> 26:04.250
I don't think I'm doing it right.

26:04.252 --> 26:06.108
Oh, here, let me

26:06.110 --> 26:08.639
- show you what she likes.
- Okay.

26:08.641 --> 26:10.048
Hey, hey.

26:10.050 --> 26:11.901
(SIGHS)

26:15.003 --> 26:17.068
(ADAKU SCOFFS)

26:17.070 --> 26:18.890
- You know her better than I do.
- (CHUCKLES)

26:18.892 --> 26:20.692
I've been taking care of Michelle.

26:20.694 --> 26:21.744
Of course I learned a few tricks

26:21.746 --> 26:23.543
- along the way.
- (SIGHS)

26:23.545 --> 26:26.346
Rhythmically, tap on her back like this.

26:32.281 --> 26:33.613
Yeah.

26:33.615 --> 26:37.075
Oh, come to Mommy. Yes.

26:37.077 --> 26:38.744
Come to Mommy.

26:38.746 --> 26:41.472
Oh. (SIGHS)

26:42.600 --> 26:45.584
- You okay?
- Fine.

26:45.586 --> 26:47.344
Yeah?

26:47.346 --> 26:50.180
Mina, is this hard for you?

26:50.182 --> 26:51.557
Will you miss her?

26:51.559 --> 26:54.926
Are you kidding? She's
cute and everything,

26:54.928 --> 26:57.187
but, um, I'll have my life back.

26:57.189 --> 27:00.691
(MICHELLE COOING)

27:00.693 --> 27:04.370
Are Dax's next set
of labs in? Thank you.

27:04.372 --> 27:07.604
- They're cooking.
- (PAGER BEEPING)

27:07.606 --> 27:10.263
Oh, damn it. Just stay on the line.

27:10.265 --> 27:11.672
<i>I'm being paged to Dax's room.</i>

27:11.674 --> 27:14.780
- What's going on?
- I'm not sure. Just listen in.

27:14.782 --> 27:18.542
(MACHINES BEEPING)

27:18.544 --> 27:20.878
Okay, he is rapidly alternating

27:20.880 --> 27:22.662
between fast and slow heart rates.

27:22.664 --> 27:23.997
<i>Tachy-brady syndrome, but why?</i>

27:23.999 --> 27:26.500
No, he's too young for
primary cardiac disease.

27:27.068 --> 27:29.567
And his echo from a few
months ago was normal.

27:29.569 --> 27:32.247
His muscle cells are
bursting into his bloodstream.

27:32.249 --> 27:34.496
Yeah, making it likely
an electrolyte issue.

27:34.498 --> 27:36.206
We need a point-of-care chem-8.

27:38.564 --> 27:40.975
Sodium 134, bicarb 22,

27:40.977 --> 27:43.141
<i>glucose 110, potassium 6.9.</i>

27:43.143 --> 27:45.202
He needs calcium and bicarb.

27:45.204 --> 27:47.404
Need an amp of calcium
gluconate and bicarb now,

27:47.406 --> 27:49.354
then an amp of D50 and
ten of regular insulin.

27:49.356 --> 27:51.525
<i>I'm not sure how this fits
into his underlying condition.</i>

27:51.527 --> 27:53.002
This is odd.

27:53.004 --> 27:55.212
- What now?
- His abdomen is distended.

27:55.214 --> 27:56.385
Reggie? Patrick?

27:56.387 --> 27:58.340
- What are you thinking? <i>
- I'm just, I'm worried</i>

27:58.342 --> 28:00.200
<i>his splenic lac has opened
up and he's starting</i>

28:00.202 --> 28:02.114
to rebleed. Take him down to CT

28:02.116 --> 28:03.606
- and find out what's going on.<i>
- I want to help.</i>

28:03.608 --> 28:05.848
<i>I need to know. So keep me posted.</i>

28:05.850 --> 28:08.184
<i>Okay. I will.</i>

28:08.186 --> 28:12.096
Thank you.

28:12.098 --> 28:13.701
That call about your patient?

28:13.703 --> 28:16.525
- Yeah.
- Thank you.

28:16.527 --> 28:17.985
Getting worse.

28:21.348 --> 28:23.056
Listen, you're doing
everything you can do.

28:23.058 --> 28:25.851
Don't beat yourself up.

28:25.853 --> 28:29.113
You're gonna be back
in the trenches soon.

28:29.115 --> 28:30.539
How's the job hunt going?

28:30.541 --> 28:32.399
Rough.

28:32.401 --> 28:35.164
Found some hospitals in
Tennessee that look promising.

28:35.166 --> 28:37.287
(EXHALES) Tennessee?

28:37.289 --> 28:39.865
Yeah, I got fired. I'm
poisoned goods in Atlanta.

28:39.867 --> 28:43.091
And after my run-in with
my dear friend Logan Kim,

28:43.093 --> 28:44.795
the poison's gonna spread statewide.

28:44.797 --> 28:47.247
Okay, so you're just gonna give up?

28:47.249 --> 28:50.741
I'm persona non grata.
I'm out of options.

28:50.743 --> 28:55.255
I'm sorry, I'm looking for
the table with Conrad Hawkins.

28:55.257 --> 28:57.215
Come on, man.

28:57.217 --> 28:59.473
Look, you're always telling us
to fight, think outside the box.

28:59.475 --> 29:00.760
That's what I've been doing.

29:00.762 --> 29:02.721
I can't keep fighting the
same battle and losing.

29:02.723 --> 29:03.822
I have to move on.

29:03.824 --> 29:05.908
Listen,

29:05.910 --> 29:08.410
you are the guy that pulls
Hail Marys out of nowhere.

29:08.412 --> 29:10.821
And guys like you, they don't just

29:10.823 --> 29:12.564
think outside the box, they create

29:12.566 --> 29:13.916
their own box if necessary,

29:13.918 --> 29:15.584
and then you think out of that one, too.

29:16.829 --> 29:19.255
What's going on with your patient?

29:22.364 --> 29:23.979
She had a cerebellar stroke,

29:23.981 --> 29:26.175
and then she started to herniate,

29:26.177 --> 29:29.149
so they did a posterior craniectomy.

29:29.151 --> 29:32.959
Red Rock prioritizes surgical
patients over ER patients.

29:32.961 --> 29:34.178
It's more lucrative.

29:34.180 --> 29:36.371
So ER patients that should be upstairs

29:36.373 --> 29:38.774
in a room are being
boarded in the hallway.

29:38.776 --> 29:40.634
And that's what happened
to my patient today.

29:40.636 --> 29:43.020
It delayed us realizing
she was having a stroke.

29:43.022 --> 29:46.287
- So do something about it.
- There's nothing I can do.

29:46.289 --> 29:49.480
Oh, yeah, I'm-I'm sorry,
I was looking for the table

29:49.482 --> 29:52.270
- with Devon Pravesh.
- (CHUCKLES)

29:52.272 --> 29:54.481
No, it-it's... that's
not the same thing.

29:54.483 --> 29:57.626
Patient boarding...

29:57.628 --> 29:59.203
that's a national crisis.

29:59.205 --> 30:01.371
Okay.

30:01.373 --> 30:03.823
So you find the local solution
to the national problem.

30:03.825 --> 30:05.992
If I have to think outside

30:05.994 --> 30:08.245
of the box for my unwinnable
situation, so do you.

30:08.247 --> 30:10.956
(CHUCKLES)

30:10.958 --> 30:12.832
I miss this.

30:12.834 --> 30:13.976
(SIGHS)

30:13.978 --> 30:16.395
Yeah, me, too.

30:36.408 --> 30:38.375
Dad, open the door.

30:43.841 --> 30:45.841
Dad.

30:45.843 --> 30:48.010
I think I know what you're planning,

30:48.012 --> 30:50.012
and I'm not gonna let you do it.

31:06.555 --> 31:08.105
NIC: I'm... (SIGHS)

31:08.107 --> 31:11.575
I'm worried you might
be a danger to yourself.

31:13.612 --> 31:15.779
That's a pretty big leap, but I get it.

31:15.781 --> 31:18.023
You're upset about what I said earlier.

31:18.025 --> 31:21.735
We are rebuilding our lives, together,

31:21.737 --> 31:23.528
and things are really good.

31:23.530 --> 31:28.033
And I think it caught you by surprise.

31:28.035 --> 31:30.368
When you came back to help Jessie,

31:30.370 --> 31:34.223
you didn't expect that the man

31:34.225 --> 31:37.059
who burns everything down

31:37.061 --> 31:41.397
would start building things
he was scared to lose.

31:41.399 --> 31:43.691
(STAMMERS) You're-you're
just making this a lot harder

31:43.693 --> 31:46.223
than it has to be. I really
think you need to leave.

31:46.225 --> 31:49.071
You and I both know if
I walk out that door,

31:49.073 --> 31:51.573
- I'll never see you again.
- Nic, if you love me,

31:51.575 --> 31:53.409
you will go.

31:53.411 --> 31:55.435
No.

31:55.437 --> 31:57.732
Because every day for
the rest of my life,

31:57.734 --> 31:59.990
I will live with the guilt
that I walked out on my father

31:59.992 --> 32:01.834
when he needed me, so, no.

32:04.422 --> 32:07.131
It won't be your fault.

32:09.760 --> 32:12.594
I'm the broken wheel in this family,

32:12.596 --> 32:16.098
and this, today, I can free you of that.

32:18.177 --> 32:21.211
And I don't want you to
shed a single tear for me.

32:21.213 --> 32:23.939
I don't deserve it. I never have.

32:23.941 --> 32:26.318
Do you remember when they took me in

32:26.320 --> 32:28.760
for Jessie's transplant surgery?

32:28.762 --> 32:31.930
I wanted to tell you something.

32:31.932 --> 32:35.284
Yeah. (SNIFFLES)

32:35.286 --> 32:37.602
What was it?

32:37.604 --> 32:41.531
If I died saving Jessie,

32:41.533 --> 32:44.618
it'd be the only good thing
that I've ever done with my life.

32:47.035 --> 32:49.034
I know that I'm worthless.

32:49.036 --> 32:50.709
That's why I-I run,

32:50.711 --> 32:55.712
it's why I, I-I, I fail
at everything I touch.

32:55.714 --> 33:00.000
God... he just keeps
choosing the wrong one of us.

33:01.962 --> 33:04.629
First your mother.

33:04.631 --> 33:05.981
Jessie.

33:11.063 --> 33:13.155
I'm at the end of my life.

33:15.567 --> 33:18.077
And that is all I got to show for it.

33:20.739 --> 33:23.073
The sum total of my life...

33:23.075 --> 33:26.502
(CHUCKLES): stuffed into an envelope.

33:26.504 --> 33:28.820
That is not true.

33:28.822 --> 33:34.301
Things haven't always been easy
with us, but... you have me.

33:36.329 --> 33:37.346
(SNIFFLES)

33:37.348 --> 33:39.372
(EXHALES)

33:39.374 --> 33:43.427
I'm sorry I didn't tell
you this sooner, but...

33:43.429 --> 33:48.673
when I think about my
future... I see you in it.

33:48.675 --> 33:53.437
At my wedding, walking
me down the aisle.

33:53.439 --> 33:54.991
Birthdays, holidays,

33:54.993 --> 33:57.574
and every moment in
between, you are there.

33:59.703 --> 34:02.746
It would break my
heart if you were gone.

34:04.191 --> 34:05.666
So, no.

34:06.860 --> 34:08.585
I'm not leaving.

34:15.409 --> 34:17.594
Will you be honest with me?

34:20.632 --> 34:23.391
Can you tell me what you are planning?

34:24.710 --> 34:26.603
(CRYING)

34:29.141 --> 34:30.774
Dad.

34:34.387 --> 34:35.387
Okay.

34:36.407 --> 34:39.149
- Sorry.
- Okay. Okay.

34:39.150 --> 34:41.034
Will you give it to me, please?

34:42.228 --> 34:43.871
It's okay.

34:46.608 --> 34:48.324
- Okay.
- (CRYING)

34:48.327 --> 34:50.293
Okay.

34:55.283 --> 34:58.076
- I'm scared.
- It's okay. It's okay.

34:58.078 --> 35:00.012
(EXHALES)

35:06.660 --> 35:08.424
Bell, what happened?

35:08.426 --> 35:10.384
Well, I noticed his
abdomen was distended,

35:10.386 --> 35:12.015
and then his hemoglobin took a dive.

35:12.017 --> 35:13.668
What, you're thinking
it's his splenic lac?

35:13.670 --> 35:15.468
Well, yeah, that's what
I was worried about.

35:15.470 --> 35:16.470
(BEEPS)

35:17.749 --> 35:18.816
That's what's happened.

35:18.818 --> 35:20.098
That spleen's got to
come out immediately.

35:20.100 --> 35:21.355
Whatever is going on with Dax

35:21.357 --> 35:22.784
is causing him to become coagulopathic.

35:22.786 --> 35:25.120
Well, clotting issues aside...

35:25.122 --> 35:27.105
we got to get him to the OR stat.

35:27.107 --> 35:29.547
- I hope there's time to save his life.
- All right, let's go.

35:33.464 --> 35:35.806
Hey. Hey. What is this?

35:35.808 --> 35:37.397
Patients who have been
sitting in the ER hallways

35:37.399 --> 35:39.042
for hours, waiting for a
bed on the medicine floor.

35:39.044 --> 35:41.395
A hallway in the ER
versus a hallway here.

35:41.397 --> 35:43.870
- What's the difference?
- Proximity.

35:43.872 --> 35:45.999
Doctors tend to forget about
these patients even though,

35:46.001 --> 35:47.500
technically, they're on their lists.

35:47.502 --> 35:49.794
Out of sight, out of mind.
A patient almost died today

35:49.796 --> 35:51.170
because she fell through the cracks.

35:51.172 --> 35:52.981
Administration won't allow this.

35:52.983 --> 35:55.174
It'll go back to the
way it was tomorrow.

35:55.176 --> 35:56.634
Maybe.

35:56.636 --> 35:58.177
But at least today, these patients,

35:58.179 --> 35:59.363
they won't be forgotten.

36:07.314 --> 36:09.689
BELL: We're slightly off
the midline to the fascia,

36:09.691 --> 36:12.483
- 'cause I see rectus muscle.
- AUSTIN: Agreed.

36:12.485 --> 36:14.360
Wait. Hold up.

36:14.362 --> 36:16.029
Lac.

36:16.031 --> 36:18.590
Peep the color.

36:20.177 --> 36:22.327
That doesn't even look like muscle.

36:22.329 --> 36:23.828
It's more pale than usual.

36:23.830 --> 36:25.013
AUSTIN: And look at that.

36:25.015 --> 36:26.998
It barely twitched.

36:27.000 --> 36:30.335
Well, that's odd, given
Dax's athletic background.

36:30.337 --> 36:32.596
I think we've hit the part of
the story where we find answers.

36:32.598 --> 36:35.691
Conrad? You there?

36:35.693 --> 36:39.194
I am with you every step of the way.

36:39.196 --> 36:42.889
I know what's wrong with Dax.

36:42.891 --> 36:46.159
You'll need a muscle biopsy to confirm.

36:49.397 --> 36:52.449
Mr. Landry. Hey.

36:52.451 --> 36:56.694
So, it turns out that Dax has a
genetic mitochondrial disorder.

36:56.696 --> 36:58.327
BELL: And that occurs when mitochondria

36:58.329 --> 36:59.664
fails to produce enough energy

36:59.666 --> 37:02.533
for the body to function properly.

37:02.535 --> 37:05.387
When Dax went pro, he started
doing intermittent fasting.

37:05.389 --> 37:09.466
It triggered his disorder and it
exacerbated his trauma symptoms.

37:09.468 --> 37:10.967
Is it treatable?

37:10.969 --> 37:13.025
With a specialized diet and supplements,

37:13.027 --> 37:15.138
it's likely he'll be
able to continue to play.

37:15.140 --> 37:17.733
- I can't thank you both enough.
- AUSTIN: Uh,

37:17.735 --> 37:19.901
we aren't the only
ones you should thank.

37:19.903 --> 37:22.720
BELL: We didn't make
the diagnosis alone.

37:22.722 --> 37:25.198
Conrad Hawkins was an integral part.

37:26.197 --> 37:28.172
Really?

37:36.828 --> 37:38.903
Mr. Landry?

37:38.905 --> 37:41.331
I heard what you did for Dax.

37:41.333 --> 37:43.449
I owe you a debt of thanks.

37:43.451 --> 37:45.915
Oh. Glad I could help.

37:45.917 --> 37:48.685
I also heard that Dax brought you in

37:48.687 --> 37:51.791
because our team doctor
didn't address his concerns.

37:51.793 --> 37:53.176
That's unacceptable.

37:53.178 --> 37:56.179
My players are like family to me.

37:56.181 --> 37:59.441
And this has shown me that
my family needs a doctor.

37:59.443 --> 38:02.110
I'd like that doctor to be you.

38:02.112 --> 38:03.945
(LAUGHS)

38:05.140 --> 38:07.807
Is, is this is a real offer?

38:07.809 --> 38:10.452
It is. I don't think I'll have a problem

38:10.454 --> 38:12.262
getting you a position at St. John's.

38:14.107 --> 38:18.043
So, Dr. Hawkins, what do you say?

38:30.882 --> 38:34.976
Hawkins, what are you doing here?

38:34.978 --> 38:36.836
I thought you'd like to
know I've just been hired

38:36.838 --> 38:39.389
as the new team doctor for Georgia FC.

38:39.391 --> 38:43.176
Physical therapy, medical tests,
referrals, orthopedic surgery.

38:43.178 --> 38:47.564
It's the prestige and money

38:47.566 --> 38:50.158
of a partnership with
a major sports team.

38:50.160 --> 38:54.996
Now, all of this will
remain at St. John's,

38:54.998 --> 39:00.502
unless there's another
hospital I decide to call home.

39:00.504 --> 39:04.697
Do you want Chastain
to be that hospital?

39:04.699 --> 39:09.511
Or should I just let Red Rock know

39:09.513 --> 39:12.663
you let this golden goose
slip through your fingers?

39:12.665 --> 39:14.182
You're bluffing.

39:14.184 --> 39:17.529
Bill Landry has a
contract with St. John's.

39:17.531 --> 39:19.336
A contract his lawyers
say he can get out of

39:19.338 --> 39:20.838
with a few quick phone calls,

39:20.840 --> 39:23.674
given what happened to Dax Ramsey.

39:23.676 --> 39:27.512
If I were to agree to this,
what would be the terms,

39:27.514 --> 39:29.680
moving forward?

39:29.682 --> 39:31.908
Well, you and I hug it out...

39:34.187 --> 39:37.947
... and then I decide

39:37.949 --> 39:41.951
which physicians treat
and consult Georgia FC

39:41.953 --> 39:45.422
and I monitor every aspect of team care.

39:46.625 --> 39:49.217
I'm chief resident.

39:49.219 --> 39:51.869
And I'm gonna do
whatever I think is best

39:51.871 --> 39:54.639
for my patients here at Chastain.

39:55.875 --> 39:57.375
<i>(CORK POPS)</i>

39:57.377 --> 39:59.877
- I love it. Yes, yes.
- (LAUGHS)

39:59.879 --> 40:02.213
I can't believe you pulled this off.

40:02.215 --> 40:04.508
I wish I could've seen the
look on Logan Kim's face.

40:04.510 --> 40:06.810
Oh, if you were truly
our friend, you would have

40:06.812 --> 40:08.594
recorded it so we can play it on a loop.

40:08.596 --> 40:10.480
(LAUGHTER)

40:10.482 --> 40:12.088
I have to admit, it was pretty great,

40:12.090 --> 40:13.946
but this is just the beginning.

40:13.948 --> 40:17.064
He's right. We still
have a lot of work to do.

40:17.066 --> 40:19.122
Like ousting our corporate overlords.

40:19.124 --> 40:20.916
- Which won't be an easy task.
- True,

40:20.918 --> 40:24.402
but we will get it done, together.

40:24.404 --> 40:26.329
Agreed.

40:26.331 --> 40:31.551
But first, we need to do
something about your wardrobe.

40:34.435 --> 40:36.249
Welcome home, Conrad.

40:36.251 --> 40:39.634
(LAUGHTER)

40:39.636 --> 40:41.269
(SHOUTS)

40:41.271 --> 40:43.605
- Yeah! All right.
- (LAUGHTER)

40:45.183 --> 40:48.276
(LAUGHS, GRUNTS) Yeah!

40:49.521 --> 40:51.596
(WHOOPS)

40:51.598 --> 40:52.638
- Mwah.
- Thank you.

40:52.640 --> 40:53.782
Still looks good.

40:53.784 --> 40:55.992
A toast.

40:55.994 --> 40:58.644
Here's to another day in the trenches.

40:58.646 --> 41:00.479
- (HUNDLEY WHOOPS)
- I'll drink to that.

41:00.481 --> 41:01.862
- Cheers.
- HUNDLEY: Cheers.

41:01.864 --> 41:03.274
It's good to have you back.

41:03.276 --> 41:05.752
- Cheers.
- Cheers.

41:08.781 --> 41:10.615
(SIGHS)

41:10.617 --> 41:15.136
I'm sorry I wasn't there
to celebrate with you.

41:15.138 --> 41:17.330
After the day you've had,

41:17.332 --> 41:19.498
I'm the last person
you should think about.

41:19.500 --> 41:21.309
(EXHALES)

41:24.505 --> 41:25.705
Kyle has a long road ahead,

41:25.707 --> 41:27.148
but you don't have
to do this alone, Nic.

41:27.150 --> 41:28.775
Whatever happens, I'm here.

41:30.678 --> 41:33.488
Hey. What did I say?

41:33.490 --> 41:36.533
Exactly what I needed to hear.

41:38.570 --> 41:40.829
Oh. Oh, hey, sorry.

41:40.831 --> 41:42.330
Sorry, I just... (STAMMERS)

41:42.332 --> 41:44.614
Do you...? I-Is it
okay if I borrow this?

41:44.616 --> 41:46.167
- I kind of already stuck my...
- Oh, yeah, yeah.

41:46.169 --> 41:48.244
You can keep it. You
got everything you need?

41:48.246 --> 41:52.156
Uh, yeah, yeah. You got snacks,
you got tunes, you got road map.

41:52.158 --> 41:56.202
I think we are good to go.

41:56.204 --> 41:58.704
Well, if you need anything...

41:58.706 --> 42:00.265
(QUIETLY): Yeah.

42:02.335 --> 42:04.928
Hey, so... you-you think
this place in Savannah,

42:04.930 --> 42:07.171
you really, you really
think they can help me?

42:07.173 --> 42:08.523
NIC: It's one of the best

42:08.525 --> 42:10.549
inpatient centers in the country.

42:10.551 --> 42:12.510
It's a psych joint. I get it, but good.

42:12.512 --> 42:14.195
Whatever it takes.

42:16.942 --> 42:19.275
I really want to be there
for all those moments

42:19.277 --> 42:21.077
that you talked about.

42:22.188 --> 42:24.563
Me, too.

42:24.565 --> 42:25.665
Come on.

42:27.619 --> 42:29.360
(MUTTERS)

42:29.362 --> 42:30.462
Call me on the way?

42:52.593 --> 42:54.811
We can all help prevent suicide.

42:54.813 --> 42:57.409
The National Suicide Prevention Lifeline

42:57.411 --> 43:00.310
is a national network
of local crisis centers

43:00.312 --> 43:04.103
that provides free and
confidential emotional support

43:04.105 --> 43:07.457
to those in suicidal crisis
and emotional distress

43:07.459 --> 43:10.067
24 hours a day, seven days a week.

43:10.069 --> 43:12.778
If you're struggling
with thoughts of suicide,

43:12.780 --> 43:15.364
or worried about a
loved one or a friend,

43:15.366 --> 43:17.133
help is available to you.

